# Cloud Computing Lab - Program 8
## Program 8: Demonstrate VS Code Integration with Cloud



# Step-by-Step Execution

---

## Step 1: Start the EC2 Instance

Go to:

```text
AWS Console → EC2 → Instances

Select the existing Ubuntu EC2 instance:

PG07-Static-EC2

If the instance is stopped, click:

Instance state → Start instance

Wait until the instance state becomes:

Running

Copy the Public IPv4 address of the EC2 instance.

Example:

13.201.xx.xx
Step 2: Check Security Group

Go to:

EC2 → Instances → Select PG07-Static-EC2 → Security

Open the attached security group.

Make sure inbound rule has:

Type: SSH
Protocol: TCP
Port: 22
Source: My IP or 0.0.0.0/0

For lab exam, if SSH does not connect, use:

Source: 0.0.0.0/0

SSH port 22 must be open because VS Code connects to EC2 using SSH.

Step 3: Keep PEM Key Ready

On the local Ubuntu system, the key pair should be available in Downloads:

~/Downloads/cloud-lab-key.pem

Create .ssh folder if it does not exist:

mkdir -p ~/.ssh

Copy the PEM key into .ssh folder:

cp ~/Downloads/cloud-lab-key.pem ~/.ssh/

Set correct permission:

chmod 400 ~/.ssh/cloud-lab-key.pem

This permission is required because SSH does not accept private keys with open permissions.

Step 4: Test SSH Connection from Ubuntu Terminal

Before connecting from VS Code, test SSH from normal Ubuntu terminal.

Run:

ssh -i ~/.ssh/cloud-lab-key.pem ubuntu@EC2-PUBLIC-IP

Example:

ssh -i ~/.ssh/cloud-lab-key.pem ubuntu@13.201.xx.xx

If asked:

Are you sure you want to continue connecting?

Type:

yes

After successful connection, terminal should show:

ubuntu@ip-10-1-1-xx:~$

Run:

hostname
uname -a
whoami

Expected output:

ip-10-1-1-xx
Linux ip-10-1-1-xx ...
ubuntu

Exit from EC2:

exit

If SSH works from terminal, then VS Code Remote SSH will also work.

Step 5: Install Remote SSH Extension in VS Code

Open Visual Studio Code.

Go to:

Extensions

or press:

Ctrl + Shift + X

Search:

Remote - SSH

Install the extension by Microsoft:

Remote - SSH

This extension allows VS Code to connect to remote servers through SSH.

Step 6: Open SSH Configuration File in VS Code

In VS Code, press:

Ctrl + Shift + P

Search:

Remote-SSH: Open SSH Configuration File

Select:

~/.ssh/config

or:

/home/your-username/.ssh/config
Step 7: Add SSH Configuration

Add the following block in the SSH config file:

Host PG07-Static-EC2
    HostName EC2-PUBLIC-IP
    User ubuntu
    IdentityFile /home/musaib-parveez/.ssh/cloud-lab-key.pem
    IdentitiesOnly yes

Example:

Host PG07-Static-EC2
    HostName 13.201.xx.xx
    User ubuntu
    IdentityFile /home/musaib-parveez/.ssh/cloud-lab-key.pem
    IdentitiesOnly yes

Save the file:

Ctrl + S

Important:

Host = nickname used inside VS Code
HostName = actual EC2 Public IPv4 address
User = ubuntu for Ubuntu EC2
IdentityFile = path of PEM key

Do not write the EC2 instance name in HostName.

Correct:

Host PG07-Static-EC2
    HostName 13.201.xx.xx

Wrong:

Host PG07-Static-EC2
    HostName PG07-Static-EC2

If HostName contains PG07-Static-EC2, VS Code will show:

Could not resolve hostname
Step 8: Connect to EC2 from VS Code

In VS Code, press:

Ctrl + Shift + P

Search:

Remote-SSH: Connect to Host

Select:

PG07-Static-EC2

If VS Code asks for the operating system, select:

Linux

VS Code will open a new remote window and connect to the EC2 instance.

Step 9: Verify Remote Connection

After VS Code connects successfully, open terminal in VS Code:

Terminal → New Terminal

The terminal should show:

ubuntu@ip-10-1-1-xx:~$

Run:

hostname
uname -a
whoami
pwd

Expected output:

ip-10-1-1-xx
Linux ip-10-1-1-xx ...
ubuntu
/home/ubuntu

This confirms that VS Code is connected to the AWS Ubuntu EC2 instance.

Step 10: Create Test File from VS Code Terminal

Inside VS Code remote terminal, run:

mkdir pg08-vscode-demo
cd pg08-vscode-demo
nano test.txt

Write:

PG-08 VS Code successfully connected to AWS EC2 instance.

Save:

Ctrl + O
Enter
Ctrl + X

Display the file:

cat test.txt

Expected output:

PG-08 VS Code successfully connected to AWS EC2 instance.

This shows that files can be created and edited on EC2 directly from VS Code.
